1 线性回归模型

1.1 创建模拟数据

# create df ---------------------------------------------------------------
set.seed(13)
excite <- c(rnorm(10, 8, 0.7),
            rnorm(10, 7, 0.7),
            rnorm(10, 5, 0.7)) 
edu <- c(rep("phd", 10),
         rep("master", 10),
         rep("bachelor", 10))
status <- c(rep("single", 5),
            rep("couple", 5),
            rep("single", 5),
            rep("couple", 5),
            rep("single", 5),
            rep("couple", 5))
age <- c(rnorm(15, 30, 3),
         rnorm(15, 40, 3)) %>% round(0)
df <- data.frame(excite = round(excite,1), 
                 status = factor(status, levels = c("single", "couple")), 
                 edu = factor(edu, levels = c("bachelor","master","phd")),
                 age)
df
table(df$status, df$edu)
        
         bachelor master phd
  single        5      5   5
  couple        5      5   5

1.2 t检验与虚拟变量回归模型

# 检验数据是否服从正态
df %>% 
  group_by(status) %>%
  dlookr::normality(excite)
# 检验方差齐性
car::leveneTest(excite, status, data = df)
# 方差相等的t检验
t.test(excite ~ status, data = df, var.equal = TRUE) %>% 
  broom::tidy() %>% 
  print(width = Inf)

1 Two Sample t-test two.sided  
ggbetweenstats(
  data = df,
  x = status,
  y = excite,
  type = "parametric",
  violin.args = list(width = 0),
  point.args = list(alpha = 0.8, size = 3),
  var.equal = TRUE,
  pairwise.comparisons = TRUE,
  pairwise.display = "all",
  xlab = "Status",
  ylab = "Level of Excitement",
  title = "Excitement by Status",
  ggtheme = ggplot2::theme_bw()
) +
  ggplot2::scale_color_manual(
    values = c("#528B8B", "#8B1C62"))

lm(excite ~ status, data = df) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(as.numeric(status)-1, excite)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  theme_bw()

1.3 ANOVA检验与虚拟变量回归模型

df %>% 
  group_by(edu) %>%
  dlookr::normality(excite)
car::leveneTest(excite, edu, data = df)
aov(excite ~ edu, data = df) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
lm(excite ~ edu, data = df) %>%
  broom::tidy()
df %>% 
  filter(edu %in% c("bachelor", "master")) %>%
  lm(excite ~ edu, .) %>%
  broom::tidy()
df %>% 
  filter(edu %in% c("bachelor", "phd")) %>%
  lm(excite ~ edu, .) %>%
  broom::tidy()
# ggbetweenstats ----------------------------------------------------------
library(ggstatsplot)
ggstats_edu <- ggbetweenstats(
  data = df,
  x = edu,
  y = excite,
  messages = FALSE,
  type = "parametric",
  violin.args = list(width = 0),
  point.args = list(alpha = 0.8, size = 3),
  var.equal = TRUE,
  pairwise.comparisons = TRUE,
  pairwise.display = "all",
  xlab = "Education",
  ylab = "Excitement",
  title = "Excitement by Education",
  ggtheme = ggplot2::theme_bw()
) +
  ggplot2::scale_color_manual(values = c("cyan4", "purple3", "red3"))

# 计算均值和均值差距
mean_values <- df %>% 
  group_by(edu) %>% 
  summarise(mean_value = mean(excite))

mean_diff <- mean_values$mean_value - mean_values$mean_value[1]

# 添加均值差距标签
ggstats_edu + geom_text(
  data = mean_values,
  aes(x = edu, y = max(df$excite) + 2, 
      label = paste("Diff =", round(mean_value - mean_value[1], 2))),
  vjust = 0,
  color = "blue"
)

1.4 two-way ANOVA

# two-way anova -----------------------------------------------------------
df %>% 
  group_by(edu, status) %>%
  dlookr::normality(excite)
car::leveneTest(excite ~ edu * status, data = df)
#additive model. It makes an assumption that the two factor variables are independent
aov(excite ~ edu + status, data = df) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
lm(excite ~ edu + status, data = df) %>%

1.6 交互项

# 交互项的写法
lm(excite  ~ age + status + age:status, data = df) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
lm(excite  ~ age * status, data = df) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
# 只有交互项
lm(excite  ~ age:status, data = df) %>% 
  broom::tidy()
# edu有三种分类，引入两个虚拟变量
# 引入两个虚拟变量分别与age的交互项
lm(excite  ~ age * edu, data = df) %>% 
  broom::tidy()

We fitted a linear model (estimated using OLS) to predict excite with age,
status and edu (formula: excite ~ age + status + edu + age:status). The model
explains a statistically significant and substantial proportion of variance (R2
= 0.87, F(5, 24) = 33.03, p < .001, adj. R2 = 0.85). The model's intercept,
corresponding to age = 0, status = single and edu = bachelor, is at -0.20 (95%
CI [-4.51, 4.12], t(24) = -0.09, p = 0.926). Within this model:

  - The effect of age is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.13, 95%
CI [0.02, 0.24], t(24) = 2.44, p = 0.023; Std. beta = 0.46, 95% CI [0.07,
0.85])
  - The effect of status [couple] is statistically non-significant and positive
(beta = 2.82, 95% CI [-0.54, 6.18], t(24) = 1.73, p = 0.096; Std. beta = -0.13,
95% CI [-0.44, 0.18])
  - The effect of edu [master] is statistically significant and positive (beta =
2.60, 95% CI [1.83, 3.38], t(24) = 6.91, p < .001; Std. beta = 1.59, 95% CI
[1.11, 2.06])
  - The effect of edu [phd] is statistically significant and positive (beta =
4.60, 95% CI [3.42, 5.77], t(24) = 8.08, p < .001; Std. beta = 2.80, 95% CI
[2.08, 3.51])
  - The effect of age × status [couple] is statistically non-significant and
negative (beta = -0.09, 95% CI [-0.18, 9.31e-03], t(24) = -1.86, p = 0.075;
Std. beta = -0.30, 95% CI [-0.64, 0.03])

1.13 模型可视化

1.13.1 影响效应effects::allEffects()

# install.packages("effects")
library(effects)   
lm(excite ~ status, df) %>%
  allEffects() %>%
  plot()

lm(excite ~ edu, df) %>% 
  allEffects() %>% 
  plot()

lm(excite  ~ age + status + edu + age:status, data = df) %>% 
  allEffects() %>% 
  plot(rows = 1, cols = 2) # 图形一行两列

lm(excite  ~ age + status + edu + age:status, data = df)  %>% 
  allEffects() %>%
  plot(lines = list(multiline = T),  # 两条线在同一坐标系下
       confint = list(style = "auto")) +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

NULL
lm(excite  ~ age + status + edu + age:status, data = df) %>%
  broom::tidy()

2 logit

2.1 方程估计glm()

data(trial)

m1 <- glm(response ~ age + stage,
          data = trial,
          family = binomial(link = "logit") )

m1 %>% 
  broom::tidy() %>% 
  mutate_if(is.numeric, round, 3) 
m1 %>% 
  report::report() 
We fitted a logistic model (estimated using ML) to predict response with age
and stage (formula: response ~ age + stage). The model's explanatory power is
weak (Tjur's R2 = 0.03). The model's intercept, corresponding to age = 0 and
stage = T1, is at -1.49 (95% CI [-2.74, -0.30], p = 0.017). Within this model:

  - The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.02,
95% CI [-2.76e-03, 0.04], p = 0.091; Std. beta = 0.28, 95% CI [-0.04, 0.61])
  - The effect of stage [T2] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta
= -0.54, 95% CI [-1.42, 0.31], p = 0.219; Std. beta = -0.54, 95% CI [-1.42,
0.31])
  - The effect of stage [T3] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta
= -0.06, 95% CI [-0.95, 0.82], p = 0.895; Std. beta = -0.06, 95% CI [-0.95,
0.82])
  - The effect of stage [T4] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta
= -0.23, 95% CI [-1.12, 0.64], p = 0.606; Std. beta = -0.23, 95% CI [-1.12,
0.64])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized
version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were
computed using a Wald z-distribution approximation.
# 简洁写法
m1 <- glm(response ~ age + stage, trial, family = binomial())

trial %>% 
  glm(response ~ age + stage, ., family = binomial())
